  "prompt": "How do plant cells undergo cell division without centrioles?",
  "response": "Plant cells undergo cell division, specifically mitosis and cytokinesis, without the presence of centrioles, which are found in animal cells. Instead, plant cells rely on a different structure and mechanism to organize the microtubules necessary for chromosome segregation. Here's how it works:\n\n### 1. **Spindle Formation in the Absence of Centrioles**  \n   - In animal cells, centrioles organize the **aster microtubules** of the mitotic spindle.  \n   - In plant cells, spindle microtubules are organized by **Microtubule Organizing Centers (MTOCs)**. These MTOCs are not as clearly defined as centrioles but include structures like the nuclear envelope and other cytoplasmic regions.  \n\n### 2. **Nuclear Envelope as a Key Organizer**  \n   - During prophase, the nuclear envelope in plant cells serves as a primary site for microtubule nucleation.  \n   - Microtubules polymerize from the nuclear envelope and gradually form the **mitotic spindle**, which aligns and segregates chromosomes.  \n\n### 3. **Preprophase Band**  \n   - Prior to mitosis, plant cells form a unique structure called the **preprophase band (PPB)**, which is a ring of microtubules and actin filaments around the cell cortex.  \n   - The PPB marks the future division plane and guides the positioning of the cell plate during cytokinesis.  \n\n### 4. **Cytokinesis in Plant Cells**  \n   - Unlike animal cells, which use a contractile ring of actin and myosin to pinch the cell in two, plant cells form a **cell plate** at the division plane.  \n   - Vesicles from the Golgi apparatus are transported to the center of the cell and fuse to form the cell plate, which eventually develops into the new cell wall separating the two daughter cells.  \n\n### 5. **Microtubule Dynamics in Plant Cells**  \n   - Plant cells have highly dynamic microtubules that reorganize throughout the cell cycle.  \n   - During mitosis, microtubules form the spindle apparatus and later reorganize into the **phragmoplast**, which guides the formation of the cell plate during cytokinesis.  \n\nIn summary, plant cells achieve cell division without centrioles by using alternative structures like the nuclear envelope, preprophase band, and phragmoplast to organize microtubules and ensure proper chromosome segregation and cytokinesis.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
